    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Not every user query deserves your most expensive model. A question like \"What is 12 × 14?\" does not require GPT-4o's reasoning abilities — a model that costs 16× less handles it correctly. Model routing is the practice of classifying each incoming query and forwarding it to the cheapest model that can answer it correctly. In production systems where 70–80% of queries are routine, routing cuts API costs dramatically without users noticing any quality change."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Model routing pipeline: incoming query goes to a router which classifies complexity and type, then forwards to small/fast, large/smart, or specialist models. Cost comparison table shows routing can cut bills by 60-85%."
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Rule-Based Routing"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The simplest router uses heuristics: token count, keyword presence, or intent keywords. This adds zero latency and no extra API cost. Start here before building a learned classifier."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import tiktoken\nfrom openai import OpenAI\n\nclient = OpenAI()\nenc = tiktoken.get_encoding(\"cl100k_base\")\n\nCOMPLEX_KEYWORDS = {\n    \"explain\", \"analyse\", \"analyze\", \"compare\", \"design\", \"architect\",\n    \"refactor\", \"debug\", \"implement\", \"write a\", \"create a\",\n    \"why does\", \"how does\", \"what are the trade-offs\",\n}\n\nCODE_MARKERS = (\"```\", \"def \", \"class \", \"import \", \"SELECT \", \"<html\")\n\n\ndef route_model(query: str) -> str:\n    q_lower = query.lower()\n    token_count = len(enc.encode(query))\n\n    # Long queries usually need more reasoning\n    if token_count > 300:\n        return \"gpt-4o\"\n\n    # Code present → probably a code task\n    if any(marker in query for marker in CODE_MARKERS):\n        return \"gpt-4o\"\n\n    # Complex intent keywords\n    if any(kw in q_lower for kw in COMPLEX_KEYWORDS):\n        return \"gpt-4o\"\n\n    # Everything else: short, simple query\n    return \"gpt-4o-mini\"\n\n\ndef chat(user_message: str) -> str:\n    model = route_model(user_message)\n    response = client.chat.completions.create(\n        model=model,\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": user_message}],\n        max_tokens=512,\n    )\n    print(f\"→ routed to {model}\")\n    return response.choices[0].message.content"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Classifier-Based Routing"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A learned classifier gives higher accuracy than heuristics, especially when query complexity is domain-specific. You can train a tiny classifier on a labelled dataset of queries (\"easy\" / \"hard\") using a cheap embedding + logistic regression, or use a small LLM as the classifier. The classifier overhead must be much cheaper than the savings it enables."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\nfrom openai import OpenAI\n\nclient = OpenAI()\n\n# Option A: Use a small LLM as classifier (cost: ~0.001 cents per query)\ndef classify_with_llm(query: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Returns 'simple' or 'complex'. Uses the cheapest available model.\"\"\"\n    response = client.chat.completions.create(\n        model=\"gpt-4o-mini\",\n        messages=[\n            {\n                \"role\": \"system\",\n                \"content\": (\n                    \"Classify the user query as 'simple' or 'complex'. \"\n                    \"Simple: factual Q&A, yes/no, extraction, short summaries. \"\n                    \"Complex: multi-step reasoning, code generation, analysis, comparison. \"\n                    \"Reply with one word only: simple or complex.\"\n                ),\n            },\n            {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": query},\n        ],\n        max_tokens=5,\n        temperature=0,\n    )\n    label = response.choices[0].message.content.strip().lower()\n    return label if label in (\"simple\", \"complex\") else \"complex\"  # safe default\n\n\ndef classified_chat(user_message: str) -> str:\n    complexity = classify_with_llm(user_message)\n    model = \"gpt-4o-mini\" if complexity == \"simple\" else \"gpt-4o\"\n    print(f\"Classified: {complexity} → {model}\")\n\n    response = client.chat.completions.create(\n        model=model,\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": user_message}],\n        max_tokens=512,\n    )\n    return response.choices[0].message.content"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Embedding-Based Classifier"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For higher throughput, replace the LLM classifier with an embedding + logistic regression trained on a labelled dataset. Once trained, classification is a single vector lookup — effectively free compared to an LLM call."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import pickle\nimport numpy as np\nfrom sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression\nfrom openai import OpenAI\n\nclient = OpenAI()\n\n\ndef embed(text: str) -> np.ndarray:\n    resp = client.embeddings.create(model=\"text-embedding-3-small\", input=text)\n    return np.array(resp.data[0].embedding)\n\n\n# Training (run once, then save the model)\ndef train_router(labelled_queries: list[tuple[str, str]]) -> LogisticRegression:\n    \"\"\"\n    labelled_queries: list of (query_text, label) where label is 'simple' or 'complex'\n    Typically 200–500 labelled examples is enough.\n    \"\"\"\n    X = np.array([embed(q) for q, _ in labelled_queries])\n    y = [1 if label == \"complex\" else 0 for _, label in labelled_queries]\n    clf = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000)\n    clf.fit(X, y)\n    return clf\n\n\n# Inference\nclass EmbeddingRouter:\n    def __init__(self, clf_path: str = \"router_clf.pkl\"):\n        with open(clf_path, \"rb\") as f:\n            self.clf: LogisticRegression = pickle.load(f)\n\n    def route(self, query: str, threshold: float = 0.6) -> str:\n        vec = embed(query).reshape(1, -1)\n        prob_complex = self.clf.predict_proba(vec)[0][1]\n        return \"gpt-4o\" if prob_complex >= threshold else \"gpt-4o-mini\"\n\n\nrouter = EmbeddingRouter()\n\ndef fast_classified_chat(user_message: str) -> str:\n    model = router.route(user_message)\n    response = client.chat.completions.create(\n        model=model,\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": user_message}],\n    )\n    return response.choices[0].message.content"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Cascading: Try Cheap First, Escalate on Failure"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Cascading eliminates the classification step entirely: always call the cheap model first; if its confidence or output quality is below a threshold, re-call the expensive model. This is simple to implement and handles the long tail automatically."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from openai import OpenAI\n\nclient = OpenAI()\n\nFALLBACK_TRIGGERS = (\n    \"i don't know\",\n    \"i'm not sure\",\n    \"i cannot\",\n    \"as an ai\",\n    \"i don't have\",\n)\n\n\ndef cascading_chat(user_message: str, max_tokens: int = 512) -> tuple[str, str]:\n    \"\"\"Returns (answer, model_used).\"\"\"\n    # First attempt: cheap model\n    fast_resp = client.chat.completions.create(\n        model=\"gpt-4o-mini\",\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": user_message}],\n        max_tokens=max_tokens,\n    )\n    fast_answer = fast_resp.choices[0].message.content\n\n    # Check if the cheap model hedged or declined\n    if any(trigger in fast_answer.lower() for trigger in FALLBACK_TRIGGERS):\n        print(\"Escalating to gpt-4o...\")\n        slow_resp = client.chat.completions.create(\n            model=\"gpt-4o\",\n            messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": user_message}],\n            max_tokens=max_tokens,\n        )\n        return slow_resp.choices[0].message.content, \"gpt-4o\"\n\n    return fast_answer, \"gpt-4o-mini\"\n\n# Most queries return from the cheap model in ~200ms\n# Only ~15-20% escalate to the expensive model\nanswer, used = cascading_chat(\"What is the capital of France?\")\nprint(f\"Model: {used} | Answer: {answer}\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Multi-Tier Routing with Fallback"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Production systems often combine routing tiers: a rule-based pre-filter (fastest), then an embedding classifier for ambiguous cases, with an optional LLM cascade for the remainder. This structure keeps median latency low while handling edge cases gracefully."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass\nfrom openai import OpenAI\n\nclient = OpenAI()\n\n@dataclass\nclass RoutingDecision:\n    model: str\n    tier: str\n    reason: str\n\n\ndef multi_tier_route(query: str, router: EmbeddingRouter) -> RoutingDecision:\n    # Tier 1: cheapest safe signal — token count\n    tokens = len(enc.encode(query))\n    if tokens > 500:\n        return RoutingDecision(\"gpt-4o\", \"tier-1\", \"long query\")\n\n    # Tier 2: rule-based keyword check (no API call)\n    if any(kw in query.lower() for kw in COMPLEX_KEYWORDS):\n        return RoutingDecision(\"gpt-4o\", \"tier-1\", \"complex keyword\")\n\n    # Tier 3: embedding classifier (one cheap embedding call)\n    model = router.route(query)\n    return RoutingDecision(model, \"tier-2\", \"embedding classifier\")\n\n\ndef production_chat(user_message: str) -> str:\n    decision = multi_tier_route(user_message, router)\n    print(f\"[{decision.tier}] {decision.reason} → {decision.model}\")\n\n    response = client.chat.completions.create(\n        model=decision.model,\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": user_message}],\n    )\n    return response.choices[0].message.content"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Measuring Routing Effectiveness"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from collections import defaultdict\n\nrouting_stats: dict[str, int] = defaultdict(int)\ncost_saved = 0.0\n\n# After each routed call:\ndef record_routing(model: str, input_tokens: int, output_tokens: int) -> None:\n    global cost_saved\n    routing_stats[model] += 1\n\n    # Cost delta vs always using gpt-4o\n    gpt4o_cost = (input_tokens * 2.50 + output_tokens * 10.0) / 1_000_000\n    actual_cost = {\n        \"gpt-4o\": gpt4o_cost,\n        \"gpt-4o-mini\": (input_tokens * 0.15 + output_tokens * 0.60) / 1_000_000,\n    }.get(model, gpt4o_cost)\n    cost_saved += gpt4o_cost - actual_cost\n\ndef print_routing_report() -> None:\n    total = sum(routing_stats.values())\n    for model, count in routing_stats.items():\n        print(f\"  {model}: {count} calls ({count/total:.1%})\")\n    print(f\"  Estimated savings vs always-gpt-4o: ${cost_saved:.2f}\")"
          }
        ]
      },
